","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Epps","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>(h)apse</i>, <i>(h)aspe</i> ‘aspen tree, white poplar’ (Old English <i>æpse</i>, <i>æspe</i>). Generally, this was a topographic name for someone who lived by an aspen tree or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example Apps in Surrey, Apse Manor on the Isle of Wight, or The Asps in Warwickshire.","English: perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Eppe</i>, a possible survival of Old English <i>Eoppa</i>, or its female counterpart <i>Eoppe</i> (Latinized in post-Conquest records as <i>Eppa</i>), probably from a stem <i>eorp-</i> ‘red’. Alternatively, <i>Eppe</i> may derive from Old Norse <i>Øpi</i>, perhaps from the stem <i>øp-</i> found in the verb <i>øpa</i> ‘to cry out, shriek’.","American shortened form of   Van Epps  , a surname of Dutch origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Van Epps","meanings":["Americanized form of Dutch   Van Eps  .","History: <i>Van Epps</i> was a familiar name in the Schenectady–Albany area; Fultonville, NY, was formerly called Van Epps Swamp."]},{"name":"Eppes","meanings":["Altered form of English   Epps  .","Dutch: variant of   Eppens  ."]},{"name":"Epes","meanings":["English: variant of   Epps  ."]},{"name":"Apps","meanings":["English: variant of   Epps  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":85,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs John Epps was born about 1370, in Kent, England. She had at least 1 son with John Epes I."},"et":{"about 1370–":"umbes 1370–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1390–1425":"1390–1425","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1425":"1425","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1455":"1455","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","Old Romney, Kent, England":"Old Romney, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1370–":"noin 1370–Kuollut","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1390–1425":"1390–1425","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","about 1370":"noin 1370","1425":"1425","about 1390":"noin 1390","1455":"1455","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","Old Romney, Kent, England":"Old Romney, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fr":{"about 1370–":"environ 1370–Décédée","1360–Male":"1360–Décédé","1390–1425":"1390–1425","1370–Female":"1370–Décédée","about 1370":"environ 1370","1425":"1425","about 1390":"environ 1390","1455":"1455","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","Old Romney, Kent, England":"Old Romney, Kent, Angleterre","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs John Epps est née environ 1370, à Kent, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec John Epes I."},"de":{"about 1370–":"um 1370–Verstorben","1360–Male":"1360–Verstorben","1390–1425":"1390–1425","1370–Female":"1370–Verstorben","about 1370":"um 1370","1425":"1425","about 1390":"um 1